EIGEN Token Model: Will it Work?
Nikhil Chaturvedi
Kunal Goel
Seth Bloomberg

May 3, 2024 ⋅  11 min read

Prompt

EigenLayer, the Ethereum restaking protocol, recently announced the EIGEN token and its distribution to points holders via stakedrop. Despite being one of the most sought-after airdrops this cycle, the token and its distribution have ensnared the crypto community in heated debates.

With over $160M in venture funding raised and over $15B in TVL amassed over a few months, EigenLayer’s momentum has been consistently moving in one direction. They have also been consequential in launching the Liquid Restaking Token (LRT) space, which has amassed over $9B in TVL. These signals have made expectations for the EIGEN token and its airdrop high enough to drive interest toward protocols like Pendle to create venues for users to farm points.

But just a few days ago, the whitepaper on the details of the EigenLayer token and stakedrop was released, and crypto twitter is divided on the token design and distribution. This begs the question of the efficacy of their design and how it impacts their long-term success.

Primer

EigenLayer is a protocol that enables the reuse of Ethereum-staked security to external applications and services rather than fragmenting security and having to bootstrap it from scratch. The protocol consists of four main components: Stakers, Actively Validated Services (AVSs), Operators, and Governance.

  • Stakers: are individuals or parties restaking their staked ETH to secure AVSs in exchange for some reward/incentive.
  • AVSs: are any service built on top of EigenLayer that utilizes restaked security, such as a DA layer, an oracle, or even app chains. AVSs pay for this by distributing their native token or fees generated to restakers and operators. ETH, being the second most in-demand digital asset and having a lower interest rate premium than most other tokens, allows projects to gain access to cheap economic security rather than bootstrapping demand for their own token.
  • Operators: are individuals or parties that run the software for AVSs. This could include running validators, provers, or other specialized functions. Restakers delegate their tokens to Operators, and the rewards generated by the AVS are distributed to both parties.
  • EigenLayer governance: Is facilitated by the EIGEN Universal Intersubjective Work Token, which will be discussed below.

Problem Area

Faults & Work Tokens

In crypto, faults are systems that reward or punish actors for protecting a decentralized network from adversarial attacks. Despite there being multiple types of faults, there are two that are relevant to decentralized infrastructure:

  • Objective Faults: These are deterministic situations where a clear mathematical or cryptographic “right” or “wrong” is present in a single venue. An example of this is whether a transaction occurring on Ethereum mainnet is valid or not. The event is a verifiable objective action where all parties are present on Ethereum, and therefore, rewards or punishments can be distributed to the appropriate parties, such as slashing.
  • Intersubjective Faults: These are also deterministic situations with a clear “right” or “wrong,” but the methods to determine this and the parties involved might be disjointed. An example of this would be a price oracle responsible for accurately bringing pricing information onchain but displaying an incorrect price for USDC at $100. Any party would be able to determine that this is incorrect. Still, there is no ability to objectively determine this onchain and penalize the oracle since all the parties involved are separate and not all on Ethereum.
  • Subjective Faults: These are non-deterministic situations with, in some cases, opinionated answers. An example could be prediction markets around who the next US President will be, which are opinionated to start but ultimately have a deterministic answer. A more opinionated example would be determining the best DeFi team, which has a less deterministic answer.

Work tokens are created with objective faults in mind. They are typically provided to those that offer some specialized service to a network and also grant the ability to punish adversarial members. Currently, one primary model for work tokens is specialized objective work tokens. These tokens can only be used for a limited scope of tasks, and the completion or neglect of the task above must be attributable onchain. For example, ETH is allotted to those who validate or delegate to secure the network. It also grants the ability to punish adversarial members via slashing if they submit invalid transactions.

Ethereum is great at dealing with objective faults like invalid transactions. Still, the crypto space has expanded past this with other components, such as bridges, oracles, rollups, provers, and other pieces of infrastructure, that play a large role. Previously, there was no way to make the security and penalties more homogeneous and predictable since many of these components fall outside the Ethereum protocol's scope. The EIGEN token seeks to bridge this gap.

Token Model

Together, the EigenLayer protocol and the EIGEN token, create two new types of work tokens:

  • Universal Objective Work Tokens: Through restaking, EigenLayer has now expanded the “specialized” scope of ETH from purely being a work token to secure the Ethereum blockchain to be able to secure infrastructure and services outside of the core Ethereum protocol. However, this process is still limited to functions with a precise, verifiable, and deterministic output on Ethereum.
  • Universal Intersubjective Work Tokens: Introducing the EIGEN token to the EigenLayer protocol removes the above-discussed limitation. Together, there is the ability to expand Ethereum's economic security beyond the Ethereum blockchain and objective tasks. This can include securing DA layers, Oracles, Bridges, other L1s, etc.

Two Token System & Forking

One of EigenLayer’s value propositions is to extend Ethereum's crypto-economic security to any third party through restaking and slashing. Slashing occurs through the EIGEN tokens ability to fork. Users stake their tokens on the forked option they feel is correct and burn their tokens on the “adversarial” fork. This simulates slashing as any bad actor that keeps their tokens on an invalid fork will lose their capital. Here is how EigenLayer has created a forkable token:

  • Setup phase: Token holders come together to cement the expected outcomes and rules for a particular intersubjective fault. For example, token holders could decide that a particular Oracle using EigenLayer needs to be accurate within two basis points, and anything outside of that is considered an intersubjective fault warranting a slashing event of some agreed amount of tokens.
  • Execution phase: If the agreed-upon rules in the setup phase are violated, they are executed, resulting in a fork that can result in slashing for any bad actors.

A predictable issue can arise from a token that is forking all the time, how does this impact DeFi protocols and exchanges that have the EIGEN token? Traditionally this would put the responsibility on users, protocols, and exchanges to continuously support the newest version of the token which can be a difficult task. To solve this EigenLayer has a two-token system:

  • EIGEN: This is used for DeFi and trading purposes and is a wrapper over bEIGEN. If an EIGEN tokenholder wants to participate in intersubjective staking, they can unwrap their token. The opposite can be done if they are not interested in participating. This reduces the burden from exchanges and DeFi protocols from having to keep updating tokens to the newest fork.
  • bEIGEN: “Backing Eigen” is solely used for intersubjective staking towards AVSs.

Analyst Insights

Nikhil

With controversy regarding the EIGEN token being discussed extensively, there has been growing conversation around the efficacy of the token model.

One point brought up is what an AVS gains from offloading intersubjective staking to EIGEN rather than its own native token. Some responses critiqued the EIGEN model, stating that native token holders would be more informed on protocol information than EIGEN holders. That may be true but the point of EIGEN is to create a specialized system that deals well with intersubjective faults and can easily fork.

Say an Oracle AVS used its own native token instead of EIGEN for intersubjective staking. In the event of an asset being mispriced and there needs to be a fork to implement a punishment, all token holders of the AVS regardless of if they are involved in the intersubjective staking will need to change their token to the newest forked asset. This means assets deposited as liquidity on Uniswap, being used on a CEX, or sitting in cold storage for a long term investor will need to be exchanged. The EigenLayer two token system is designed with this in mind where one token is focused on intersubjective staking and forking while the other is a consistent canonical token used for DeFi.

The same can be said for arguments being made on what the point of EIGEN is if you can just restake ETH. As discussed in the “Primer”, restaked ETH deals with objective faults but without an easier and more seamless way to fork it would be overburdened if it were responsible for intersubjective faults. EIGEN takes the burden off of ETH similar to it being done for AVS tokens. The same principle applies, if ETH forks then this could affect exchanges, retail holders, defi protocols, etc.

The main unlock in the short term is that EigenLayer brings better UX to Social consensus than any existing blockchain token could.

Kunal

There are two sides to the EIGEN discussion. On one side, there are problems with some choices made by the EigenLayer team for the EIGEN stakedrop. EigenLayer has cleared some of these in its recent announcement, however, there are still concerns with the high insider allocation (>50%) and an odd snapshot date. The high team and investor allocation is a concern because as a Proof-of-Stake token, it is harder to decentralize the distribution than if it were a Proof-of-Work token. In contrast, UNI, one of the longest surviving and prominent applications on Ethereum with a famed airdrop, had about ~40% insider allocation. The other concern is the snapshot date of March 15 while the announcement was made on April 29. Typically, teams snapshot contributing wallets much closer to the announcement date so they are fairly rewarded. Here, late depositors miss out on Season 1’s rewards.

However, these discussions over the details of the stakedrop the forest for the trees. The more important discussion is on the token's fundamental design. EIGEN, being an intersubjective slashing token, is an entirely new design. It is a much better design than if it were a rent-seeking token that reduces the protocol's P2P efficiency or a pure governance token that has unclear value accrual. It is particularly exciting for me because my model on demand for security describes the token's value accrual.

Simply speaking, an AVS will demand security for objective and intersubjective faults from EigenLayer based on its design and appetite. Against this security demand, it must pay ETH restakers and EIGEN stakers a portion of its revenue or inflation. The demand and supply for intersubjective security will create an equilibrium where the “price of security” settles. As the ecosystem grows on top of EigenLayer, the demand for intersubjective security will likely increase, driving greater competition for it and leading to a higher price of security. This higher price will drive more EIGEN to be staked and once the staking ratio finds an equilibrium, the price of EIGEN must rise to meet security demand. The logic above can be extended to ETH by replacing “intersubjective security” with “objective security” and “staking” with “restaking”. In this, EigenLayer seems to create a win-win for EIGEN and ETH.

The key determinant, however, is the growth of EigenLayer’s ecosystem and that makes sense. Tying the success of the token with the growth of the ecosystem makes for good tokenomics and ensures that the incentives are aligned.

Seth

EigenLayer’s two-token model seemingly benefits both EIGEN token holders and AVSs seeking an out-sourced security model. An AVS can opt to leverage EIGEN as an additional form of security, thereby driving more demand for the EIGEN token.

However, it remains to be seen how much real demand there will be for EIGEN staking from AVSs. As EigenLayer states, ETH is already the “Universal Work Token” used for slashing against “objectively attributable” faults (e.g., a double spend). These faults are “clearly verifiable onchain.” So, the initial question becomes: How many AVSs need staked or restaked security beyond what ETH provides? One possible answer — only AVSs that assign non-negligible value to “offchain” features or components of its service. Ultimately, this will be decided on a case-by-case basis.

AVSs that do see value in obtaining this additional security will need to decide whether to use the native AVS token, the EIGEN token, or a combination of them. The prevailing assumption here is that holding the EIGEN token will be less risky than holding a new AVS token. Based on this assumption, the payout rate should be lower for EIGEN-based security than for AVS token-based security.

This is logical, but an AVS must consider the EIGEN approach's marginal costs and benefits. Using EIGEN may reduce payouts (i.e., native AVS token emissions to restakers), but it also reduces demand for the native AVS token and potentially increases sell pressure. It’s very likely that payouts will primarily, if not completely, be in the form of native AVS tokens (i.e., not generated revenue or fees). Restakers who earn these rewards will need strong incentives or some perceived upside in holding the AVS token rather than selling it. On the other hand, if restakers see an upside in holding the AVS token, by definition, the token should have some significant value. This then begs the question, why not just use the AVS token and ditch the EIGEN token?

Even outside of these more economical questions, technically configuring an AVS to account for EIGEN staking has its own set of challenges. As more AVSs come on board and into production via EigenLayer, I expect every AVS will need to work through these sets of considerations.
